    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a sunset clause in a Queensland property contract?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A sunset clause is a contract term that allows either the buyer or the seller to terminate a contract if a specified condition, typically completion or settlement, has not occurred by a set date. In off-the-plan contracts, it is most commonly used to allow either party to walk away if the development has not reached practical completion or title registration by the sunset date. In standard established property contracts, sunset clauses occasionally appear for developments awaiting subdivision registration."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What did Queensland change about sunset clauses in 2024?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Queensland introduced amendments to the Body Corporate and Community Management Act affecting off-the-plan contracts. The changes restricted sellers from using sunset clause terminations opportunistically to rescind contracts and resell at higher prices in a rising market. Sellers who wish to trigger a sunset clause in an off-the-plan contract must now provide written notice and buyers have additional protections, including the right to seek compensation in certain circumstances."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does a sunset clause apply when selling an established home in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Sunset clauses are uncommon in standard Queensland contracts for established homes. The standard REIQ contract of sale does not include one. They can appear in private contracts involving a development component, such as a sale conditional on subdivision registration. For most sellers of existing residential property, sunset clauses are not a relevant consideration unless the contract has been drafted specifically to include one."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

