      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Is a Sunset Clause in a Queensland Property Contract?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Sunset clauses appear most often in off-the-plan contracts. Here is how they work, what the 2024 Queensland rule changes mean, and when they are relevant for sellers of established homes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A sunset clause is a term in a property contract that sets a deadline for the occurrence of a specific event, usually practical completion of a development or registration of a plan of subdivision. If that event does not happen by the specified date, one or both parties have the right to terminate the contract without penalty. The clause exists to manage the inherent uncertainty of property development, where construction delays, planning complications, or changes in circumstances can leave buyers and sellers locked into contracts for longer than either anticipated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where sunset clauses are most common</h2>
      <p>Sunset clauses are standard in off-the-plan contracts, where a buyer is purchasing an apartment, townhouse, or house and land package before the development has been completed or the title registered. The buyer is committing to a purchase that will not settle until an unknown future date, which may be one year away or several years away depending on the development timeline. The sunset clause gives both parties a defined endpoint: if the development is not registered by a certain date, either party can walk away.</p>

      <p>They also appear in contracts involving subdivision of existing lots, where a seller is selling a portion of land that does not yet have a separate title. The contract is conditional on the plan of subdivision being registered, and the sunset clause sets the outer limit on how long the buyer and seller must wait.</p>

      <p>Standard established home contracts in Queensland, using the REIQ contract of sale, do not include sunset clauses as a default term. If you are selling an existing house with registered title, a sunset clause is not a standard feature of your contract and does not apply unless someone has specifically drafted one in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a sunset clause protects both parties</h2>
      <p>From the buyer's perspective, the sunset clause prevents indefinite exposure to a contract where the development keeps getting delayed. Without it, a buyer could be locked in for years, unable to pursue other purchases, while the developer manages delays. The sunset clause gives the buyer a defined exit point if the project does not proceed as expected.</p>

      <p>From the seller's or developer's perspective, the sunset clause provides certainty about the outer limits of their obligations. If circumstances change significantly, and the development genuinely cannot be completed within the agreed timeframe, the sunset clause provides a mechanism to end the contract rather than remaining in ongoing breach.</p>

      <p>The practical tension is that sunset clauses in a rising market create an incentive for developers to allow the sunset date to lapse, so they can terminate contracts executed at lower prices and resell at current values. This is the problem the 2024 Queensland legislative changes were designed to address.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 2024 Queensland rule changes</h2>
      <p>Queensland introduced significant changes to the Body Corporate and Community Management Act and related legislation affecting off-the-plan contracts and sunset clause terminations. The core concern prompting the changes was that developers were using sunset clauses opportunistically during the property boom. A developer would sign contracts, allow the sunset date to pass without completing the development, and terminate the contracts. They would then relaunch sales at significantly higher prices, leaving original buyers with nothing but the return of their deposit.</p>

      <p>The 2024 amendments introduced buyer protections including: requirements for sellers to provide notice before triggering a sunset clause termination, a buyer right to seek compensation in circumstances where a termination is found to have been triggered in bad faith or without reasonable cause, and additional disclosure obligations around sunset dates in off-the-plan contracts. These changes align Queensland more closely with reforms that New South Wales introduced earlier in response to similar conduct by developers in the Sydney market.</p>

      <p>For buyers purchasing off-the-plan in Queensland after the 2024 changes, the position is more protective than it was previously. For sellers who are developers, the changes mean that allowing a sunset date to lapse and terminating contracts opportunistically carries legal risk that did not exist under the previous framework.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Sunset clauses and established home sales</h2>
      <p>For most sellers of existing residential property in Brisbane, sunset clauses are not a day-to-day concern. The REIQ contract of sale that covers the vast majority of inner-east residential transactions does not include one. Your contract will have finance conditions, building and pest conditions, and a settlement date, none of which are sunset clauses in the technical sense.</p>

      <p>Where a sunset clause can appear in an established property context is when the sale involves a future element, such as a simultaneous subdivision, or when a private or commercial contract has been drafted with one included. If you see a sunset clause in a contract presented to you as a seller, it is worth understanding exactly when it can be triggered and by whom. A clause that only the buyer can trigger is asymmetric in a way that may not suit you. A clause with a very short sunset date on a complex transaction may be unrealistic and create unnecessary risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens when a sunset clause is triggered</h2>
      <p>When a sunset clause is triggered in accordance with its terms, the contract is terminated. The deposit is returned to the buyer, and both parties are released from their obligations under the contract. There is no penalty on either side for a termination that complies with the clause. The question of whether a termination is lawful depends on whether the triggering party has followed the required notice procedures and whether the conditions for termination have actually been met.</p>

      <p>In the context of the 2024 Queensland changes, a seller who triggers a sunset clause where the development could have been completed within the timeframe, or where there is evidence the delay was manufactured to obtain a resale price advantage, risks a compensation claim from the buyer. This is a litigation risk that responsible developers and their legal teams are now actively managing.</p>

      <p>For buyers and sellers in standard residential transactions, the sunset clause is largely a background concept rather than a live issue. It becomes relevant when you are purchasing off-the-plan or entering a contract with development conditions attached. In those circumstances, having the clause reviewed carefully by your solicitor before you sign is one of the most valuable pieces of legal advice you can obtain.</p>

